  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Rhyming Poem on Official Inspection in Seungpyeong County
  author: Choi Young-yeo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Autumn comes—the geese already follow the southbound sun.
    Touched by the world's affairs, my sorrow flows without end.
    A few white points on the sand—are they not herons?
    All the yellow by the roadside—surely they are tangerines and pomelos.
    The colder the mountain grows, the more I love its lean and gaunt form.
    With ripened grain, fragrance spreads its rich and mellow warmth.
    Burdened with the weight of royal commission and duty,
    I raise my cup, yet cannot revel as in days of old.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem is written during an official inspection tour in Seungpyeong County, creating tension between aesthetic observation and administrative responsibility.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of autumn—migrating geese, sparse herons, ripening crops—traditionally evokes melancholy and transience in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet contrasts the speaker's desire for carefree enjoyment with the gravity of official obligations, suggesting the restraint demanded by high office.
